---

<CaseLayout title="Cockpit View 2.0 — Sivanesh TV" caseNum="01" caseName="Cockpit View 2.0">
  <Fragment slot="reader">
    <ReaderColumn>
      <Hero
        eyebrow="case study · 01"
        title='Cockpit View <em>2.0.</em>'
        sub="Redesigning the primary control interface for autonomous drone operations — from the ground up."
      />

      <MetaRow items={[
        { k: 'Role', v: 'Lead · with Prathamesh' },
        { k: 'Year', v: '2026' },
        { k: 'Scope', v: 'Product Design · Prototype/Simulations' },
        { k: 'Tools', v: 'Figma · Claude suite · Docs/Sheets' },
      ]} />

      <ImgSlot variant="wide"
        src="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-hero.png"
        alt="Cockpit View 2.0 — in-flight interface showing map, video feed, mission panel, and system controls"
        cap="Cockpit View 2.0 — in-flight, live telemetry"
        capMeta="the interface"
      />

      <!-- § 01 Context -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Context" num="§ 01" />
        <H2>Cockpit View is the <em>primary interface</em> operators live in all day.</H2>
        <Lead>It runs in a browser — no native app, no dedicated hardware — and it has to perform like both a map and a command centre at once.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>Professional drone operators use Cockpit View to control autonomous flights, monitor live video, manage missions, and respond to in-flight events. Shifts are long. Attention is finite. Every ambiguous moment in the interface translates directly into cognitive load the operator can't afford.</p>
          <p>The v1 interface had grown by accretion. Every new capability arrived as another panel, another toggle, another overlay — stacked onto a canvas originally built for far fewer concerns than it now carried.</p>
          <p>Operators had adapted. They knew where things were because they'd memorised the layout — not because the layout communicated it. The interface had lost its mental model. Every new feature we tried to add made that problem worse.</p>
          <p>The Cockpit didn't need a polish pass. It needed a rewire.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <!-- § 02 The problem -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The problem" num="§ 02" />
        <PullQuote>The interface was working. The <em>operators</em> were doing the work it should have been doing.</PullQuote>
        <Body>
          <p>We didn't have a dedicated research team. What we had was Customer Success — sitting in on calls, reading transcripts, fielding every confused operator question since v1 shipped. That was our evidence pool. And a pattern kept surfacing: operators were compensating.</p>
          <p>Memorising which panel held which control. Ignoring notifications they'd learned to filter out. Opening multiple browser tabs to see everything at once. The interface wasn't broken. It was offloading its work onto the person using it.</p>
          <p>The hard part wasn't identifying this. The hard part was <strong>deciding what to change first</strong> when the answer was <em>everything is coupled to everything</em>.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p><em>Before we could fix any screen, we had to decide which kind of signal lives where — and why.</em> That became the spine of four structural rewrites.</p></Callout>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-v1.png"
          alt="Cockpit v1 interface — the version operators were working around"
          cap={'v1 — the "it works" version operators were working around'}
          capMeta="before"
        />
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 03 Step one — Five-mechanism communication framework -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step one" num="§ 03" />
        <H2>Every signal gets one mechanism. <em>No exceptions.</em></H2>
        <Lead>The first structural decision wasn't visual — it was categorical. A grammar for how the Cockpit communicates with the operator.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>We defined five delivery mechanisms. Each anchored to a specific place on screen. Each answering a specific kind of question. The operator learns once: <em>where a signal lives tells them what kind of thing it is.</em></p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>Five wasn't where we started. The first draft had three — <em>Alerts</em> (things wrong), <em>Feedback</em> (things done), <em>Status</em> (things true). It collapsed within a week. Is a lost Dock–Drone connection an alert, or a background status the operator just needs to know about? Is an AI detection feedback, or something to act on? Is a failed subscription renewal an alert, a banner, or neither? Every new feature was a debate. We added mechanisms only when we could name the specific confusion the new one resolved. <em>Five was where the arguments stopped.</em></p></Callout>
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Alerts — top bar.</strong> Something's wrong with the drone, dock, environment, or system.</p>
          <p><strong>Toasts — viewport corner.</strong> Feedback about what the operator just did.</p>
          <p><strong>Banners — full-width strip.</strong> A platform state is affecting what's possible right now. Network lost, subscription limit, connection dropped.</p>
          <p><strong>Contextual — in the video or map feed.</strong> Something in what the operator is already looking at needs attention.</p>
          <p><strong>Right Panel — the workbench.</strong> Where the operator <em>does</em> things. Flight actions, third-party alarms, AI workflows.</p>
          <p>When a new feature arrives, the question isn't "where should this go?" — it's "which mechanism is this?" <em>No overlaps. No orphans.</em> Design reviews got shorter. The grammar did the arguing for us.</p>
        </Body>
        <MarginRef jump="panel-hierarchy">↗ see the communication framework</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-three-bucket.png"
          alt="Five communication mechanisms, each anchored to a specific place on screen"
          cap="Where signal lives tells you what it is"
          capMeta="the grammar"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 04 Step two (Alerts) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step two" num="§ 04" />
        <H2>If the alerts panel is empty, <em>that</em> should feel like good news.</H2>
        <Lead>v1 buried alerts. Critical emergencies, low-priority warnings, informational nudges — all stacked in the same list. Operators had learned to ignore them.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>v2 organizes alerts along two axes. Four categories — <strong>Airspace, Diagnostic, Weather, System</strong> — each as its own tab in the top-bar panel. And four severities — <strong>Critical, Warning, Caution, Info</strong> — each with its own colour, weight, and behaviour.</p>
          <p>Critical and Warning alerts auto-expand the panel and persist until the condition clears. Caution and Info alerts collect quietly, available when the operator chooses to look but never demanding attention they haven't earned. Each severity has a distinct visual grammar, so operators recognise "this is a critical airspace alert" from peripheral vision alone.</p>
          <p>The panel tells you when it's empty with an explicit quiet state. An empty panel should feel like a <em>status</em>, not an absence — otherwise the operator wonders whether the alert system is broken.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p><em>If there's nothing to worry about, say so.</em> Silence is a design decision, not a default.</p></Callout>
        <MarginRef jump="alerts">↗ see the alert severity grammar</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-alerts.png"
          alt="Alert grammar — four categories, four severities, one panel"
          cap="Four categories, four severities"
          capMeta="the system"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 05 Step three (Half-life) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step three" num="§ 05" />
        <H2>Every surface has a <em>half-life.</em></H2>
        <Lead>§ 03 routed signal by category — what it is. § 05 routes by duration — how long it deserves to stay.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>Some information is true for a moment. Some for an hour. Some for as long as the shift runs. The Cockpit routes each to a surface built for that time scale.</p>
          <p><strong>Always — Control Panel, bottom.</strong> Flight state the operator glances at without thinking. Horizontal and vertical speed, wind, heading. It never moves. Moving it would invalidate hours of built-up flight instinct.</p>
          <p><strong>Transient — viewport corner.</strong> Action confirmations as toasts. Success fades on its own. Failure waits until the operator has seen it. Nothing here claims permanence it hasn't earned.</p>
          <p><strong>On-demand — notification bell, top bar.</strong> Every toast that fades lands here — timestamped, searchable, held for as long as the operator needs it. Quick glance or permanent record, in one place that answers both.</p>
        </Body>

        <ImgSlot variant="square"
          src="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-feedback.png"
          alt="Feedback architecture — three destinations, zero overlap"
          cap="Transient, ambient, on-demand"
          capMeta="the routing"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 06 Step four (Layout) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step four" num="§ 06" />
        <H2>Boring chrome. <em>Flexible body.</em></H2>
        <Lead>v1's biggest complaint wasn't what things did. It was that things <em>moved</em>. Muscle memory never formed.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>v2 freezes the chrome. The frame around the Cockpit never shifts — same places, every shift, every mission. Three view modes (<strong>Map, Split, Video</strong>) change what fills the body, never what sits around it.</p>
          <p>That's the trust contract. Boring, on purpose. Chrome the operator's hand finds without looking.</p>
        </Body>

        <Callout><p>Inside that frozen frame, we gave operators something v1 never had — real ownership of their workspace.</p></Callout>

        <Body>
          <p>In Split view, the divider is draggable — pull Map to 70% for survey work, push it down to 30% when the video feed is the job. Swap Map and Video sides entirely if that's how your team thinks. The Cockpit remembers. Every ratio, every position, every preference — the Cockpit an operator logged out of is the Cockpit they log back into.</p>
          <p>Different missions build different bodies. Same chrome. <em>Certainty where it matters. Sovereignty where it helps.</em></p>
        </Body>

        <BeforeAfter
          before="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-v1-layout.png"
          after="/assets/cockpit/cockpit-v2-layout.png"
          beforeLabel="v1 · before"
          afterLabel="v2 · after"
          beforeAlt="Cockpit v1 layout — panels jostle, nothing has a home"
          afterAlt="Cockpit v2 layout — fixed chrome + modular body"
          cap="Layout comparison — drag to compare v1 and v2"
          capMeta="before / after"
        />
        <p style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);text-align:center;margin-top:-18px;margin-bottom:24px">— the single most important image in this case —</p>
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 07 Outcomes -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What happened" num="§ 07" />
        <H2>The receipts.</H2>

        <Outcome items={[
          { n: 'Live', l: 'Deployed', d: 'Shipped as the primary interface across FlytBase enterprise deployments — the surface every operator flies from.' },
          { n: '0', l: 'Exceptions', d: 'Since shipping, every new feature has slotted into the five-mechanism grammar without needing a sixth. The framework held.' },
          { n: 'Kept', l: 'By operators', d: 'No significant layout-discoverability complaints post-launch — the kind of silence that, in critical-ops interfaces, is the loudest win you can get.' },
        ]} />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 08 Reflection -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What I took away" num="§ 08" />
        <Body>
          <p><strong>The framework decides, not you.</strong> Once "every signal gets one mechanism" was a principle, half my design decisions stopped being my decisions. A feature request that didn't fit was a signal about the request, not the framework. The rule did the hard work of saying no so I didn't have to have the same conversation five times.</p>
          <p><strong>Boring is a feature.</strong> In critical-ops interfaces, surprising is almost always bad. The best thing you can do for the operator is build chrome they can forget about, and give them sovereignty over the parts that should feel like theirs.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <EndRow note="— end of case · § 01 / 02 —" nextLabel="Next: Fleet View ↗" nextHref="/fleet" />
    </ReaderColumn>
  </Fragment>

